  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in nearly all jurisdictions worldwide. It involves the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by transferring it through a complex sequence of banking or commercial operations. This activity is criminalized because it enables the integration of illicit funds into the legitimate financial system, often derived from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or terrorism.\n\nMost countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, requiring financial institutions and other businesses to implement measures to detect and prevent it. For example, the U.S. has the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the Patriot Act, while international frameworks like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) provide guidelines for countries to follow. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. China, as a responsible member of the international community, also has strict anti-money laundering laws and actively participates in global efforts to combat financial crimes.",
